    <sec>
      <title>CASE REPORT</title>
      <p>A 12-year-old dark-skinned male patient was admitted at the dermatology service with
the following characteristics: hypertelorism, macroglossia, lentigines, hypospadias,
cryptorchidism, subaortic stenosis, growth retardation, and about 50% of his hearing
compromised (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="f1">Figure 1</xref>). Electrocardiogram
showed a prolonged PR interval. The patient had a severe anterior open bite (no
contact of the upper and lower front teeth) due to macroglossia (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="f2">Figure 2</xref>). His legal guardian reported that he
had been treated for patent ductus arteriosus and for cryptorchidism, hypospadias,
subaortic stenosis, and blue nevus on his arm and back. He had also undergone
tonsillectomy and adenoidectomy. Regarding family background, the patient was the
second child of a healthy, nonconsanguineous young couple. He had a sister and a
brother without symptoms.</p>
